syllable /ˈsɪləbəl/

(syllables) 

1. N-COUNT A syllable is a part of a word that contains a single vowel sound and that is pronounced as a unit. So, for example, 'book' has one syllable, and 'reading' has two syllables. 音节 

例： We children called her Oma, accenting both syllables. 我们这些孩子叫她，两个音节都重读。

